    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>New York</placeName>
                <date>17th April 1864</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd I Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Friend,</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I have delayed this<lb/> long replying to your last two
                let<lb/>-ters, hoping to get sufficient time<lb/> to pay <persName>Mrs
                    Lawrence</persName> a visit that<lb/> I might speak to her about your<lb/>
                various publications; but as I have<lb/> yet not been able to do so, I will<lb/> no
                longer defer thanking you for<lb/> the kind manner in which you<lb/> responded to
                our appeal, &amp; beg to<lb/> inform you that every thing has been<lb/> accomplished
                to our entire satisfaction<lb/> through your kind introduction to</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the <persName>Rev Dr Bondi</persName> We are much<lb/> pleased with the Rev Dr &amp;
                think him<lb/> a perfect gentleman in his manner<lb/> as well as one well conversant
                with<lb/> the Law; and I am truly grateful to<lb/> think we were saved from
                falling<lb/> into the hands of <persName>Mr Phillips</persName>, whom<lb/> I
                apprehend to be a man too mercenary<lb/> to have a proper view of a conversion<lb/>
                One of the first questions he asked me<lb/> was “if the gentleman could afford<lb/>
                to give as much as <persName>Mr Lawrence</persName>;” and<lb/> he endeavored to
                impress on my mind<lb/> the necessity of keeping it secret; and<lb/> as much as
                possible from the know<lb/>-ledge of the <persName>Revd I M Isaacs</persName>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">We regret that a succession of<lb/> disappointments &amp; troubles
                should<lb/> have so long prevented us from<lb/> liquidating our indebtedness to</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>you and trust you will accept<lb/> the enclosed Twenty Five Dollars<lb/> as a portion
                of the same, the receipt<lb/> of which please acknowledge by post</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Hoping to have the pleasure<lb/> of seeing you on your next
                visit<lb/> to this city, I remain,</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">Yours respectfly</p>
            <p rend="indent(11)">
                <persName role="author">J. Palache</persName>
            </p>
            <pb n="Envelope"/>
            <p>THE <persName>MISSES PALACHE'S</persName></p>
            <p>FRENCH &amp; ENGLISH</p>
            <p>BOARDING &amp; DAY SCHOOL,</p>
            <p><placeName>No. 174 West 37th St.</placeName>,</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>NEW YORK</placeName>.</p>
